Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which underpins the euro by establishing constraints determining the size of the budget deficits of member states of the Union, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has failed to meet its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Furthermore, it has used its political weight to cover up the early warning of its deficit, set up by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the stability pact.
Today it's France that's playing the bad boy.
The second-in-command of the Union, rather unenthusiastic, is now officially declaring that it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, a year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a true disaster.
In fact, Europe seems to be very affected by the discussions aiming to eliminate it, as well as the discussions aiming to amend it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation poorly done.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of the GDP is arbitrary and without consideration of the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
By admitting this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "ill-conceived" solutions.
They introduced a safety clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is almost impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns might breach the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget projection for the next two years showing how the budget balance will be achieved in due time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable rate.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a budgetary contraction policy.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized that they could all face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, including tax reduction.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it's not just a matter of political intelligence, it's also a matter of economic intelligence, as long as budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges financed by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely unpopular.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the Union's laws.
Political maneuvers will follow, inevitably.
Economists and cynics are hardly surprised.
The pact's objective, to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is quite reasonable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, member states now benefit from only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Promising to go on a diet before a big party is not easy to reconcile.
The stability pact is too crude and technocratic: the 3% target set by the Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining flexible enough in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy has achieved real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it's enough to delegate this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any mishap will have to be resolved in the future, it's up to it to use common sense.
This has proven to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Of course, some fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditures and revenues.
The decisions concerning these matters cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage fluctuation cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent organization.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain total control over its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure the outcome of such a Committee, its status and mandates must be agreed upon within the Union without interference from Brussels, arbitrary regulations, or political decision-making, but simply relying on common sense.
